Key Concepts

- **Root** is UID 0 — the most powerful user
- `/etc/passwd` — user info (world-readable)
- `/etc/shadow` — password hashes (root only)
- `/var/log/` — system logs
- `/tmp/` — writable by all users (often used in privesc)
- SUID bit (`chmod +s`) — run as file owner, not caller

-----

Key Commands

 Navigation

pwd           # Print working directory
ls -la        # List all files with permissions
cd /path      # Change directory
find / -name "file.txt" 2>/dev/null  # Find files


 File Operations

cat file.txt         # Read file
nano / vim file.txt  # Edit file
cp src dst           # Copy
mv src dst           # Move/rename
rm -rf dir/          # Delete recursively

Permissions

chmod 777 file    # rwxrwxrwx
chmod 644 file    # rw-r--r--
chown user:group file

Permission breakdown:
- r = 4, w = 2, x = 1
- Owner | Group | Others

User Management

whoami
id
sudo su
adduser username
passwd username
cat /etc/passwd
cat /etc/shadow    # Hashed passwords


Process Management

ps aux            # All running processes
top / htop        # Real-time process viewer
kill -9 PID       # Force kill process

 Networking

ifconfig / ip a   # Network interfaces
netstat -tulpn    # Open ports
ss -tulpn         # Modern netstat
ping 8.8.8.8

Package Management (Debian/Ubuntu)

apt update && apt upgrade
apt install <package>
apt remove <package>
dpkg -l           # List installed packages


Useful Shortcuts

Ctrl+C    # Kill current process
Ctrl+Z    # Suspend process
Ctrl+L    # Clear terminal
!!        # Repeat last command
sudo !!   # Repeat last command as sudo
